        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<div style="background-size:cover;background-repeat:no-repeat;position:relative;background-image:url(&quot;data:image/jpeg;base64,&quot;);width:350px;display:block;margin:0 auto"><svg style="width:100%;height:auto;max-width:100%;margin-bottom:-4px" width="640" height="853"></svg><noscript><img style="width:100%;height:auto;max-width:100%;margin-bottom:-4px;position:absolute;top:0;left:0" src="/assets/ideal-img/glass-block-lamp-1.4d38d93.640.jpg" srcset="/assets/ideal-img/glass-block-lamp-1.4d38d93.640.jpg 640w,/assets/ideal-img/glass-block-lamp-1.8a57eae.1030.jpg 1030w" alt="The finished glass block lamp" width="640" height="853"></noscript></div><br><p>I love mood lighting, and my home is filled with various lava lamps, quirky bulbs, and other fun lights.<br>
To add a personal touch to my collection, I thought it would be a fantastic idea to create one myself!
I've had my eye on a glass block lamp for quite some time, and now it's the perfect opportunity to make it happen.
To take the visual concept up a notch, I decided to incorporate some fancy RGB electronics ðŸŒˆ.</p><h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="tools">Tools<a href="#tools" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Tools" title="Direct link to Tools">â€‹</a></h2><ul><li>A 3D printer : I used my Prusa Mini+</li><li>A soldering station : I used a Aixun T3B, <a href="https://youtu.be/Ds2Xq3dwV30" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">it's great</a></li><li>A computer with Google Chrome to configure the WLED software</li><li>Precision screwdrivers</li><li>UV glue : I used Bostik Fix &amp; Flash</li></ul><h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="materials">Materials<a href="#materials" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Materials" title="Direct link to Materials">â€‹</a></h2><p>For this project, I used the following materials:</p><ul><li>A glass block : I used a 19x19x8cm one which I bough at my local hardware store, Leroy Merlin</li><li>An ESP32 microcontroller : I used an <a href="https://www.adafruit.com/product/5400" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Adafruit ESP32 Feather V2</a></li><li>3 Adafruit RGBW NeoPixel sticks : I used <a href="https://www.adafruit.com/product/2867" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">these ones from Adafruit</a>. They're great but expensive... See the <a href="https://kno.wled.ge/basics/compatible-hardware/#addressable-led-strips" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">WLED Documentation</a> for compatibility with other LED strips.</li><li>A TSOP38238 IR receiver</li><li>A <a href="https://kno.wled.ge/interfaces/infrared/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">compatible</a> IR remote</li><li>A potentiometer : I used a 10kÎ© one as recommended by the <a href="https://kno.wled.ge/features/macros/#global-brightness" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">WLED documentation</a></li><li>A 5V 3A USB-C power supply : I used one made for the Raspberry Pi 4.</li><li>Black PLA (for the case assembly) and white PLA (for the diffuser) : I used <a href="https://prusament.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Prusament</a> and <a href="https://fillamentum.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fillamentum</a> PLA.</li><li>Prototyping wire</li><li>M2 screws and heat-set inserts</li></ul><div class="theme-admonition theme-admonition-caution alert alert--warning admonition_LlT9"><div class="admonitionHeading_tbUL"><span class="admonitionIcon_kALy"><svg viewBox="0 0 16 16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M8.893 1.5c-.183-.31-.52-.5-.887-.5s-.703.19-.886.5L.138 13.499a.98.98 0 0 0 0 1.001c.193.31.53.501.886.501h13.964c.367 0 .704-.19.877-.5a1.03 1.03 0 0 0 .01-1.002L8.893 1.5zm.133 11.497H6.987v-2.003h2.039v2.003zm0-3.004H6.987V5.987h2.039v4.006z"></path></svg></span>ESP32 microcontroller compatibility</div><div class="admonitionContent_S0QG"><p>WLED is currently not fully compatible with ESP32-S2, ESP32-S3 or ESP32-C3 microcontrollers, see <a href="https://github.com/Aircoookie/WLED/issues/966" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">#966</a>, <a href="https://github.com/Aircoookie/WLED/issues/2735" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">#2735</a>, <a href="https://github.com/Aircoookie/WLED/issues/1940" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">#1940</a>.
Use a regular ESP32 to be sure.</p></div></div><h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="modeling-the-case">Modeling the case<a href="#modeling-the-case" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Modeling the case" title="Direct link to Modeling the case">â€‹</a></h2><p>TODO</p><h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="electronics-wiring">Electronics wiring<a href="#electronics-wiring" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Electronics wiring" title="Direct link to Electronics wiring">â€‹</a></h2><p>TODO</p><h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="assembly">Assembly<a href="#assembly" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Assembly" title="Direct link to Assembly">â€‹</a></h2><p>TODO</p><h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="programming">Programming<a href="#programming" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Programming" title="Direct link to Programming">â€‹</a></h2><p>TODO</p><h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="todo">TODO<a href="#todo" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to TODO" title="Direct link to TODO">â€‹</a></h2><ul><li>keep writing this article</li><li>write a note about sourcing glass blocks</li><li>add project sources (stl, wled config, etc.). Maybe on GitHub ?</li><li>add related documentation links (remove them from the text ?)</li><li>Add improvement ideas</li></ul>]]></content>
